            <!-- Theory & explanation -->
            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>What is a circular segment?</h2>
              <p>
                A <strong>circular segment</strong> is the region of a circle
                cut off by a chord. It is bounded by:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>a straight line (the chord), and</li>
                <li>the corresponding arc of the circle.</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                If you draw a chord across a circle and shade only the “cap”
                between the chord and the circle, you get a circular segment. In
                many applications (fluid levels in tanks, structural design,
                optics, surveying) we know the radius and one extra measure such
                as the segment height, chord length, or central angle and need
                the segment area.
              </p>

              <h3>Key geometry and notation</h3>
              <p>We will use the following notation:</p>
              <ul>
                <li><span class="font-mono">R</span> – circle radius</li>
                <li>
                  <span class="font-mono">h</span> – segment height (sagitta),
                  measured from the chord to the circle along the symmetry axis
                </li>
                <li><span class="font-mono">c</span> – chord length</li>
                <li>
                  <span class="font-mono">θ</span> – central angle corresponding
                  to the segment (in radians)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <span class="font-mono">A_seg</span> – circular segment area
                </li>
                <li>
                  <span class="font-mono">A_sec</span> – circular sector area
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Formulas for circular segment area</h2>
              <p>
                The fundamental formula for the area of a circular segment in
                terms of radius and central angle (in radians) is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">
                  Segment area from radius and central angle
                </p>
                <p>
                  Given a circle of radius <span class="font-mono">R</span> and
                  central angle <span class="font-mono">θ</span> (radians),
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2">
                  <span class="font-mono">A_sec = (1/2) · R² · θ</span> &nbsp;
                  (sector area)
                </p>
                <p>
                  <span class="font-mono">A_tri = (1/2) · R² · sin θ</span>
                  &nbsp; (area of isosceles triangle formed by the two radii and
                  the chord)
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2">
                  <span class="font-mono"
                    >A_seg = A_sec − A_tri = (R² / 2) · (θ − sin θ)</span
                  >
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>From radius and segment height (R, h)</h3>
              <p>
                The segment height <span class="font-mono">h</span> is related
                to the central angle via
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><span class="font-mono">cos(θ / 2) = (R − h) / R</span></p>
                <p class="mt-2">
                  so
                  <span class="font-mono">θ = 2 arccos( (R − h) / R )</span>.
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2">
                  Once <span class="font-mono">θ</span> is known, use
                  <span class="font-mono">A_seg = (R² / 2) · (θ − sin θ)</span>.
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Valid segments satisfy
                <span class="font-mono">0 &lt; h &lt; 2R</span>. When
                <span class="font-mono">h = 0</span>, the segment collapses to
                the empty set; when <span class="font-mono">h = 2R</span>, it
                covers the whole circle.
              </p>

              <h3>From radius and chord length (R, c)</h3>
              <p>The chord length and central angle are related by:</p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><span class="font-mono">c = 2R · sin(θ / 2)</span></p>
                <p class="mt-2">
                  so
                  <span class="font-mono">θ = 2 arcsin( c / (2R) )</span>.
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2">
                  The segment height can also be computed as
                  <span class="font-mono">h = R − √(R² − (c/2)²)</span>.
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2">
                  Again, use
                  <span class="font-mono">A_seg = (R² / 2) · (θ − sin θ)</span>.
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Geometrically, <span class="font-mono">0 &lt; c &lt; 2R</span>.
                As <span class="font-mono">c → 0</span>, the segment shrinks
                away; as <span class="font-mono">c → 2R</span>, it approaches a
                semicircle.
              </p>

              <h3>From radius and angle (R, θ)</h3>
              <p>
                When the central angle is known (for example, from geometry or
                trigonometry), the computation is direct:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">
                  Segment quantities from R and θ (radians)
                </p>
                <ul class="list-disc">
                  <li>
                    <span class="font-mono"
                      >A_seg = (R² / 2) · (θ − sin θ)</span
                    >
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <span class="font-mono">A_sec = (R² / 2) · θ</span> (sector
                    area)
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <span class="font-mono">c = 2R · sin(θ / 2)</span> (chord
                    length)
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <span class="font-mono">h = R · (1 − cos(θ / 2))</span>
                    (segment height)
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <span class="font-mono">L_arc = R · θ</span> (arc length)
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <h2>Interpreting the calculator output</h2>
              <p>For any valid input combination, the calculator reports:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Segment area</strong>
                  <span class="font-mono">A_seg</span>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Sector area</strong>
                  <span class="font-mono">A_sec</span>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Full circle area</strong>
                  <span class="font-mono">πR²</span>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Chord length</strong>
                  <span class="font-mono">c</span> and
                  <strong>arc length</strong>
                  <span class="font-mono">L_arc</span>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Central angle</strong> in both radians and degrees
                </li>
                <li><strong>Segment perimeter</strong> (chord + arc)</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Percentage</strong> of the full circle occupied by the
                  segment
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                As long as you keep your length units consistent, you can safely
                use the results in engineering drawings, volume calculations
                (for partially filled circular tanks), structural checks, and
                educational examples.
              </p>
            </section>

            <!-- FAQ (HTML, tied to FAQPage schema) -->
            <section class="mt-8" id="faq">
              <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4">
                Circular Segment Area – FAQ
              </h2>
              <div class="space-y-3" id="faq-container">
                <article class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <button
                    type="button"
                    class="w-full text-left flex justify-between items-center faq-question"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium text-sm"
                      >Can this calculator handle very small or very large
                      segments?</span
                    >
                    <span class="ml-2 text-gray-400">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div class="faq-answer mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700 hidden">
                    Yes. The formulas are valid for any segment with 0 &lt; h
                    &lt; 2R (or equivalently 0 &lt; c &lt; 2R and 0 &lt; θ &lt;
                    2π). For extremely thin caps or almost complete circles,
                    round-off error may appear in the last decimal places, but
                    the qualitative behavior remains correct. If you are
                    designing safety-critical structures, consider adding an
                    independent analytic or numerical check.
                  </div>
                </article>

                <article class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <button
                    type="button"
                    class="w-full text-left flex justify-between items-center faq-question"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium text-sm"
                      >Why does the calculator need radians for the internal
                      formulas?</span
                    >
                    <span class="ml-2 text-gray-400">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div class="faq-answer mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700 hidden">
                    The standard trigonometric formulas for segment and sector
                    area use the central angle measured in radians, because many
                    expressions like sin θ and θ naturally appear in calculus
                    and geometry. To keep the interface user-friendly, you can
                    enter the angle in degrees; the calculator converts degrees
                    to radians internally and applies the formulas in a
                    numerically stable way.
                  </div>
                </article>

                <article class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <button
                    type="button"
                    class="w-full text-left flex justify-between items-center faq-question"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium text-sm"
                      >What happens if my inputs don’t satisfy the geometric
                      constraints?</span
                    >
                    <span class="ml-2 text-gray-400">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div class="faq-answer mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700 hidden">
                    If the chord length is greater than 2R, if the height is
                    negative or at least 2R, or if the angle is outside the
                    valid range, there is no real circular segment with those
                    parameters. In these cases, the calculator detects domain
                    violations and displays clear error messages instead of
                    producing misleading numbers.
                  </div>
                </article>

                <article class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <button
                    type="button"
                    class="w-full text-left flex justify-between items-center faq-question"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium text-sm"
                      >Can I use the results to compute volumes in partially
                      filled circular tanks?</span
                    >
                    <span class="ml-2 text-gray-400">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div class="faq-answer mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700 hidden">
                    Yes. For a horizontal cylindrical tank, the liquid
                    cross-section at a given fill height is a circular segment.
                    Once you know the segment area, you can multiply it by the
                    tank length to get volume. This calculator focuses on the
                    cross-sectional geometry; for full tank-volume problems, you
                    can combine it with a dedicated volume calculator or
                    engineering design reference.
                  </div>
                </article>
              </div>
